<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://store1.yimg.com/I/scibook_1679_1118"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
If you want to make your way to the past, then your best bet is to find a convenient black hole equipped with a traversable wormhole. If the future is more your style, then get on a spaceship that travels just under the speed of light. With a tongue-in-cheek approach, renowned astrophysicist and science popularizer Davies shows how &quot;a limited form of time travel is certainly plausible.&quot; Through lots of illustrations and straightforward text, he illustrates just how time-traveling contraptions would be built and what scientific principles would fuel them.<br>
<br>
Some of the knottier physics Ågneed not concern us hereÅh, says Davies. ÅgWhat matters... is that time is elastic.Åh If you accelerate far enough, fast enough, less time will pass for you than for those you left behind; hover near a superdense neutron star, and gravity will slow time by 30 per cent; harvest a wormhole from the space - time foam, and you may be able to visit the past or the future, and change the present.<br>
<br>
It is an easy read with no index and nearly as many pictures (diagrams explain the quirks of space-time) as words.<br>
<br>
He tells us that before we can build our own time machine, you need to stabilise our wormhole with ÅgantigravityÅh (very hard to do) from a generous source of Ågnegative energyÅh (very hard to find). Even if we succeed, we will probably get turned into spaghetti or less nice body parts. Davies's eventual conclusion undermines the upbeat title. How do you build a time machine?<br>
<br>
Well, sorry, it's too difficult and it costs too much. We can't.<br>
<br>
Damn!<br>
